name: Big Huckleberry Creek
description:
Introduction

An unassuming, overlooked creek in the proximity of the popular Panther Creek Falls in Gifford Pinchot National Forest. While it doesn't sport many rappels, Big Huckleberry is a beautiful canyon and an enjoyable day out - particularly in the spring when the creek has good water. It's more fun than the nearby Eightmile Creek.

  • Checkpoint: From the Panther Creek Falls parking area (old quarry) walk east up FR-65 for two minutes to where it crosses Big Huckleberry Creek. This is the exit.
  • Watershed: 1.92mi^2.

Approach

Drop a car at the bottom and shuttle up to the top. Probably high clearance best per a couple rough spots. In 2021, the last mile or so was a bit brushy, so we parked and hiked in rather than risk the pin-striping. If you can get through, there are pullouts for a few cars just before and after the creek.

Either drop in and head downstream, or follow the ridge on the east side of the creek and drop in before the confluence.

Descent

Believing there wasn't much of interest in the upper creek, the original descent team paralleled the creek for perhaps 15min before dropping in to discover a nice section of bedrock with some mini-slides. Next time, we'll drop in up at the road. There might even be one more short rappel up there.

  • R1: 50ft old rootball DCL.

Ahead Big Huckleberry Creek plunges into an amphitheater and another tributary of equal size - and another waterfall - enters from the east. For extra bonus points, set a rim rope ahead of time. You can run the falls, then ascend back up, bushwhack over to the tributary and run that waterfall too.

  • R2: 100ft tree DCL. Very photogenic falls.
  • Bonus rappel on the east tributary: Falls is about 60ft high, but need about 150ft SRT to get down per the horizontal distance. Anchor is a tree set well back DCR.

Note that the flow downstream of R2 will double. Continue on your way. Eventually, enter another area of nice bedrock that kicks off with a short slide into a deep narrow pool. This bedrock area leads to R3.

  • R3: 45ft.

Continue downstream with occasional downclimbs and mini-slides to keep you on your toes. Very lush beautiful Pacific Northwest canyon. There is one mini-downclimb through a very short narrows.

  • R4: 20ft.

Exit

Exit the creek DCR up to the road. Walk west down the road to the Panther Creek trailhead (2 min).

Red tape

Please resist the temptation to run the nearby Panther Creek Falls while you're here. The area above and below Panther Creek Falls has been closed to entry since a woman fell to her death in 2018. Unlike other parts of the country, canyoning is not widely known or recognized in the Pacific Northwest. Individuals climbing, rappelling, or slack-lining around such "show waterfalls" are far more likely to garner negative reactions from the general public at large. Negative reactions can lead to complaints and more rules for canyoneers by the local authorities.

Background

First descended by Wade Hewitt, Kevin Clark, Andy Sorensen, Leah Sorensen, Emily Joy, and David Urbaniak in May 2021.
